The problem states that the energy threshold \( E_{th} \) required to produce electron-hole pairs is given by \( E_{th} = \frac{3}{2}kT \). Setting this equal to the energy gap \( E_g \), we solve for \( T \): \[ E_g = \frac{3}{2}kT \] Rearranging to solve for \( T \): \[ T = \frac{2E_g}{3k} \] Given: - The energy gap for germanium \( E_g = 0.742 \, \text{eV} \) - Boltzmann's constant \( k = 8.617 \times 10^{-5} \, \text{eV/K} \) Substituting the values into the equation: \[ T = \frac{2 \times 0.742 \, \text{eV}}{3 \times 8.617 \times 10^{-5} \, \text{eV/K}} \] First, calculate the numerator: \[ 2 \times 0.742 = 1.484 \, \text{eV} \] Next, calculate the denominator: \[ 3 \times 8.617 \times 10^{-5} = 0.00025851 \, \text{eV/K} \] Now, divide the numerator by the denominator: \[ T = \frac{1.484}{0.00025851} \approx 5745 \, \text{K} \] Convert this temperature from Kelvin to Celsius: \[ 5745 \, \text{K} - 273.15 = 5471.85 \, ^\circ\text{C} \] Rounding to one decimal place, we get: \[ 5471.85 \, ^\circ\text{C} \approx 5.5 \times 10^3 \, ^\circ\text{C} \] Thus, the temperature at which germanium becomes conductive is \(\boxed{5.5 \times 10^3}\) degrees Celsius.
